    {
      "text": "A 28-year-old woman presents to the gastroenterology clinic with complaints of chronic abdominal pain, diarrhoea, and weight loss over the past several months. She reports experiencing frequent episodes of diarrhoea, often with mucus and blood. A colonoscopy was performed, which showed multiple aphthous ulcers scattered throughout the terminal ileum and proximal colon. A biopsy was done, which is shown below. What is the most likely diagnosis?",
      "options": [
        {
          "label": "A",
          "text": "Ulcerative colitis",
          "correct": false
        },
        {
          "label": "B",
          "text": "Irritable bowel syndrome",
          "correct": false
        },
        {
          "label": "C",
          "text": "Crohn\u2019s disease",
          "correct": true
        },
        {
          "label": "D",
          "text": "Diverticulitis",
          "correct": false
        }
      ],
      "correct_answer": "C. Crohn\u2019s disease",
      "question_images": [
        "https://image.prepladder.com/notes/7FQuWimHGbURzAIwT4or1744375760.png"
      ],
      "explanation_images": [
        "https://image.prepladder.com/notes/oiO8vz4f2FYB759B7HUw1744375901.png",
        "https://image.prepladder.com/notes/GQ5oYzgSYR37z3L6GLpT1744376562.png"
      ],
      "explanation": "<table cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; width:NaN\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p><strong>Endoscopic/gross findings</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p><strong>Microscopic findings</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p><strong>Aphthous ulcers</strong> (<strong>earliest finding</strong>): May progress, and multiple lesions often coalesce into elongated, serpentine ulcers oriented along the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3c28fd47f71692777182efbbaa5f6d\">axis</span> of the bowel.</p>\n</td>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p>Abundant <strong>neutrophils infiltrate</strong> and damage the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d2a83e1b4c1692777185c446d81c0c\">crypt</span> epithelium.</p>\n<p><strong>Submucosal <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"32599f889a169277719169e3483e62\">lymphoid</span> aggregates</strong> may also be seen.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p>Edema and loss of normal mucosal folds.</p>\n</td>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p>Clusters of neutrophils within a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d2a83e1b4c1692777185c446d81c0c\">crypt</span> are <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"047f8930dd1692777197fed61e213c\">referred</span> to as <strong>crypt abscesses</strong> and are often associated with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d2a83e1b4c1692777185c446d81c0c\">crypt</span> destruction.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p><strong>Cobblestone appearance</strong> of the mucosa: Occurs due to <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"50f4196df6169277720181ef605c33\">ulceration</span> with sparing of interspersed mucosa, a result of the patchy distribution of lesions.</p>\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<figure class=\"caption_element\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"Crohns Disease Cobblestone appearance\" data-author=\"Ye, Ziyin & Lin, Yuan & Cao, Qinghua & He, Yulong & Xue, Ling\" data-hash=\"9401\" data-license=\"CC BY 4.0\" data-source=\"https://www.researchgate.net/figure/Endoscopic-features-of-intestinal-tuberculosis-ITB-and-Crohns-disease-CD_fig2_286480371\" data-tags=\"April2025\" height=\"321\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/oiO8vz4f2FYB759B7HUw1744375901.png\" width=\"387\"/>\n<figcaption>{{caption_text}}</figcaption>\n</figure>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p><strong>Epithelial metaplasia:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Pseudopyloric metaplasia.</li>\n<li>Paneth cell metaplasia.</li>\n</ul>\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<figure class=\"caption_element\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"Crohn's <span class=\" custommeta\"=\"\" data-dictid=\"e6955110f21692777184d2090a400c\"/>colitis biopsy\" data-author=\"CoRus13\" data-hash=\"9406\" data-license=\"CC BY SA 4.0\" data-source=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Crohn%27s_colitis_-_biopsy,_intermed._mag.jpg\" data-tags=\"April2025\" height=\"280\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/izmMPQ7i1qRkBtfnPAvd1744376295.png\" width=\"417\" />\n\t\t\t<figcaption>{{caption_text}}</figcaption>\n</figure>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p><strong>Fissure</strong> development is common and may extend deeply to become <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"10df63cea41692777203b470341d21\">fistula</span> tracts or sites of perforation.</p>\n</td>\n<td colspan=\"1\" rowspan=\"3\" style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\"><strong>Non-caseating granulomas</strong> are a hallmark of Crohn\u2019s disease and occur in areas of active disease or uninvolved regions within any layer of the intestinal wall.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p>The intestinal wall is thickened and rubbery as a consequence of <strong>transmural oedema, inflammation, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7cb424e4921692777199f9951be2ce\">submucosal</span> fibrosis,</strong> and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3baac9012a1692777189cb4dc70c04\">hypertrophy</span> of the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9e2d8a3f5a16927771932c2348ec52\">muscular</span> propria, all of which contribute to <strong>stricture</strong> formation.</p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p>In cases with extensive <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"53ab411c811692777200e0e1b68984\">transmural</span> disease, mesenteric <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"5c2a4a949d16927771802ba54640cc\">adipose</span> tissue frequently extends over the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"5ce9b6c57f1692777198cdc854b76a\">serosal</span> surface, known as <strong>creeping fat.</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; width:NaN\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p><strong>Endoscopic findings</strong></p>\n</td>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<p><strong>Microscopic findings</strong></p>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<ul>\n<li>Mucosal and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7cb424e4921692777199f9951be2ce\">submucosal</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"ebb480187d1692777199e233e9e356\">superficial</span> involvement.</li>\n<li>Pseudopolyps.</li>\n<li>Collar button ulcers.</li>\n<li>Backwash ileitis.</li>\n</ul>\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<figure class=\"caption_element\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"Ulcerative <span class=\" custommeta\"=\"\" data-dictid=\"e6955110f21692777184d2090a400c\"/>colitis <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"35ca8c2d5f16927771879351e8f97e\">endoscopic</span> image\" data-author=\"Samir\" data-hash=\"9409\" data-license=\"CC BY SA 3.0\" data-source=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Ulcerative_colitis.jpg\" data-tags=\"April2025\" height=\"342\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/IQ91tAcc5HzkqUs3tz9t1744376443.png\" width=\"395\" />\n\t\t\t<figcaption>{{caption_text}}</figcaption>\n</figure>\n</div>\n</td>\n<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n<ul>\n<li>Inflammatory infiltrates.</li>\n<li>Cryptitis and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"d2a83e1b4c1692777185c446d81c0c\">crypt</span> abscesses.</li>\n<li>Absence of non-caseating granulomas.</li>\n</ul>\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<figure class=\"caption_element\" style=\"display:inline-block\"><img alt=\"UC Histopathology\" data-author=\"KGH\" data-hash=\"9411\" data-license=\"CC BY SA 3.0\" data-source=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Ulcerative_colitis_(2)_active.jpg\" data-tags=\"April2025\" height=\"351\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/GQ5oYzgSYR37z3L6GLpT1744376562.png\" width=\"465\">\n<figcaption>{{caption_text}}</figcaption>\n</img></figure>\n</div>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n\n\n<p style='font-size: 10px; color: #808080; font-style: italic;'></p>",
